[[File:Mongolian yatga front view.JPG|thumb|right|A Mongolian yatga]]
===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|mn|ятга}} / {{m|mn|ᠶᠠᠲᠤᠭ᠎ᠠ}}.
===Noun===
{{en-noun}}
# A traditional plucked bridge [[zither]] played in [[Mongolia]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2001 |title=Mongolian Music, Dance, & Oral Narrative: Performing Diverse Identities |author=Carole Pegg  |page= |ISBN=0295981121 |passage=In Old Mongolia, the '''yatga''' was used in courts to entertain the aristocracy and was also played by the aristocracy. }}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2009 |title=Culture and Customs of Mongolia  |author=Timothy Michael May  |page=89 |ISBN= 031333983X|passage=Traditionally '''yatga''' performances were reserved only for monasteries and the court, and playing the instrument was considered a sacrosanct rite. This taboo changed over time as new forms of the '''yatga''' appeared, ranging from a ten-stringed '''yatga''' that anyone could play to a '''yatga''' with twenty-one strings. }}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2017|title=The Garland Encyclopedia of World Music: East Asia |author=Robert C. Provine, Yosihiko Tokumaru, & J. Lawrence Witzleben  |page= |ISBN=1351544292 |passage=The second and fourth manuscripts have musical notation for the ten-stringed '''yatga''' (Erdenechimeg and Shagdarsüren 1995).  }}
